reviewText:
DisclaimerAll that's following is an impression of a person who hasn't played MineCraft, Terraria, Starbound or any similar games so far.


Addicting, incredibly addicting… Before start please be sure you currently don’t have important things to do.

It’s about: helping little dwarfs to survive in dangerous world(s) by exploring it and developing technologies and themselves;
crafting, crafting, crafting;
“city management”, but in 2D and only on a scale of one house (or shelter);
get into troubles.
Why you should play this: because it’s good for you to help someone who’s smaller and can’t stand for oneself without getting a hand;
you like crafting-oriented games;
it’s just adorable to see how your dwarfs go through all troubles and conquering dangerous world;
you’ve always wanted to try something like Starbound or Terraria, but they look for you either too big (content-overloaded) or ugly (I’m sorry, but it’s true);
unlike Terraria or Starbound it offers indirect control - you just plan and point what to do, no reason to play solo on your keyboard or gamepad;
unlike in Terraria, items and menus quite large - no reason to screw up your eyes;
May, 21 - 4th world was added: finally, we can have GUNS and different craft tree.
Why you may not like it: Terraria and Starbound veterans will be insulted with the amount of content for crafting and lack of opportunities;
the craft tree is almost the same in first 3 worlds (there are a few tenuous changes): you develop it to maximum in one world, fix the portal to travel to another world and all that only for starting everything from scratch with the same technologies to explore; in my opinion it would be better to change not only the world's weather conditions but also time and add something truly new into craft tree;
now there are 4 worlds available for playing – there’re no hints on any kind of story or campaign: you just have to travel from one world to another and survive walking through the same stages of developing, it makes the game quite monotonous;
it doesn’t contain any save option up to your request: your actions are final, all your mistakes stay with you - you can’t replay it, game saves your progress only when you leave it;
it’s probably will take over 130 hours to beat 4 worlds (25-35 hours per world plus replays if you want all of the achievements).
Despite all flaws it’s fun, it’s entertaining – if you remember yourself playing Tamagotchi (or at least you know what it is), then give it a chance: highly likely you won’t regret.
